		<title>Read remote repository content with GitHub CLI</title>
		<link>https://github.blog/changelog/2026-06-17-read-remote-repository-content-with-github-cli</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Allison]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 17 Jun 2026 20:03:57 +0000</pubDate>
				<guid isPermaLink="false">https://github.blog/changelog/2026-06-17-read-remote-repository-content-with-github-cli</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Explore repository content from your terminal without cloning by using two new commands: gh repo read-file and gh repo read-dir. What you can do Use gh repo read-file to read&#8230;</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://github.blog/changelog/2026-06-17-read-remote-repository-content-with-github-cli">Read remote repository content with GitHub CLI</a> appeared first on <a href="https://github.blog">The GitHub Blog</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/loose.dtd">
<html><body><p>Explore repository content from your terminal without cloning by using two new commands: <a href="https://cli.github.com/manual/gh_repo_read-file"><code>gh repo read-file</code></a> and <a href="https://cli.github.com/manual/gh_repo_read-dir"><code>gh repo read-dir</code></a>.</p>
<h2 id="what-you-can-do" id="what-you-can-do" ><a class="heading-link" href="#what-you-can-do">What you can do<span class="heading-hash pl-2 text-italic text-bold" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></h2>
<ul>
<li>Use <code>gh repo read-file</code> to read an individual file from a remote repository</li>
<li>Use <code>gh repo read-dir</code> to browse a directory&rsquo;s contents from a remote repository</li>
</ul>
<p>These commands work across public and private repositories you have access to, making it faster to inspect code, documentation, and configuration files from any repository.</p>
<h2 id="use-cases" id="use-cases" ><a class="heading-link" href="#use-cases">Use cases<span class="heading-hash pl-2 text-italic text-bold" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></h2>
<p>With <code>gh repo read-file</code> and <code>gh repo read-dir</code>, you can:</p>
<ul>
<li>Quickly inspect README files or documentation without leaving your terminal.</li>
<li>Check configuration files across multiple repositories.</li>
<li>Build scripts and automation that read repository content.</li>
<li>Integrate repository exploration into AI agents and workflows.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="availability" id="availability" ><a class="heading-link" href="#availability">Availability<span class="heading-hash pl-2 text-italic text-bold" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></h2>
<p><code>gh repo read-file</code> and <code>gh repo read-dir</code> are available to all GitHub users, including those on GitHub Enterprise Server (GHES), after installing or upgrading to <a href="https://github.com/cli/cli/releases/tag/v2.95.0">GitHub CLI v2.95.0</a> or later. You can also teach your agents how to leverage new GitHub CLI features by <a href="https://github.com/cli/cli#agent-skills">installing or updating the <code>gh</code> skill</a>.</p>
<p>Learn more or give us feedback on the <a href="https://github.com/cli/cli"><code>cli/cli</code> repository</a>.</p>
</body></html>
<p>The post <a href="https://github.blog/changelog/2026-06-17-read-remote-repository-content-with-github-cli">Read remote repository content with GitHub CLI</a> appeared first on <a href="https://github.blog">The GitHub Blog</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
